The Sultan's Palace

The Sultan's Palace is not merely a haunted royal residence. It is the failed
keystone of a political experiment: an attempt to unify oasis water-law,
desert charter governance, and pyramid funerary sovereignty under one courtly
state.

After the hydraulic and institutional shocks of the Ninth Meridian
catastrophe, a mediator-lord named Kheir al-Zafir emerged as the Sultan of
Reconciled Measures. His first reform required caravan charters, household
oaths, and funerary declarations to be registered in a single palace archive.
Fewer contradictory rulings, standardized witness formats, centralized seal
verification. But it also created a single choke point. If the palace
controlled registration, it controlled legitimacy itself.

Three currents collided within its halls. Water-Court Pragmatists favored
measurable quotas and reversible judgments. Sultanate Centralists subordinated
measurement to throne prerogative. Funerary Absolutists treated death
stewardship as superior to all civic law.

As disputes intensified, the palace adopted Corrective Harmonization: the
selective rewriting of identity and obligation under the guise of reconciling
contradictory records. Families could not prove inheritance. Caravans could
not prove prior toll exemptions. Shrines could not prove burial custody.
Social order became administratively legible but existentially unstable.

The end came when palace centralists attempted a grand rite to bind aquifer
flow to dynastic succession symbols. Pressure seals ruptured. Archive vaults
flooded in sequence. Petition courts were cut off from evacuation. The event
became known as the Drowning of the Court.

Kheir al-Zafir is said to have died in the apex sanctum, clutching the
ceremonial diadem while decree-lights drowned the chamber in azure fire.
Yet court records from afterward still bear his seal, implying either forged
continuity or posthumous governance by ritual mechanism. The palace's ghosts
are not random undead but the procedural remains of a civilization that tried
to make law, water, memory, and death answer to one throne.
